text:
hello there
today's word is one that can be used as

an adjective a noun and a verb the word
is parallel as an adjective parallel

means to be of equal distance apart
without altering or changing to

continuous straight lines that sit
equally side-by-side are parallel

railway tracks appear parallel the road
runs parallel to the river

two of the letters in the word parallel
are parallel to things that exist at the

same time in similar ways are parallel
electrical components or circuits

connected to common points at each end
are parallel in computing a process that

involves two or more programs running at
the same time is parallel as a noun the

word parallel can mean a personal thing
that is similar or analogous to another

the expression of a clear similarity is
a parallel in printing the two fine

lines used to show a reference point is
a parallel as a verb the word parallel

means two things laid side by side of
equal distance from each other

to position to things in an equally
straight line with each other

is parallel in this case used with
objects the electric cable paralleled

the main road to thoughts or actions
that have a connection or similarity are

parallels they occur at the same time or
share some common action two things are

similar or correspond
the word parallel originates from the

French word parallel and before that via
Latin from the Greek paralelos which

literally means alongside each other
synonyms of parallel include similar

matching comparable equivalent
corresponding analogous the opposite of
parallel is dissimilar and unlike P A R A L L E L parallel
